<h1>Problem 236 - 2007 IMOSL, N7, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 9</h2>
<p>For a prime \(p\) and a given integer \(n\) let \(\nu_{p} (n)\) denote the exponent of \(p\) in the prime factorisation of \(n!.\) Given \(d \in \mathbb{N}\) and \({p_{1}, p_{2}, \dots p_{k}}\) a set of \(k\) primes, show that there are infinitely many positive integers \(n\) such that \(d \mid \nu_{p_{i}}(n)\) for all \(1 \leq i \leq k.\)</p>
